I live in a big city.  My neighborhood is very different.  There are homes and stores everywhere.  You can find many kinds of stores, like offices, shops, and places to eat.  There are many new places to eat and shop.  Some stores are big and famous.  Some stores are small and new. 

There are parks near my home.  People bring their children to the parks.

Many different people live in my neighborhood.  There are people from many countries.  There are people of different religions.  There are also people who speak different languages.

There are areas in the city for different groups of people.  There is Korea Town, China Town, and Little Armenia.  It is hard to drive in the city because there is a lot of traffic.  People mostly drive cars.

There are many new buildings in the city.  People like to live here.  Some people do not like this because there will be more traffic.

There are many different kinds of homes in the city.  Some people live in big apartment buildings.  Some people live in small houses.  Some people live in houses with two families.

There are people of all ages in my neighborhood.  I do not know all of my neighbors.  When I was a child, I played with my neighbors.

My neighborhood is special. Many houses are single.  Some houses are cut in two, but they share a wall. My house has a small yard in front and a small driveway. It looks like houses from long ago. People used to want to live here. They called it the American dream. Many people liked it. But now, not so many. My neighborhood is still here. It shows that people still want this dream. People are not as happy as before. Yards are not as nice. But there are cars in each driveway. Kids play.

The school is old, almost ninety years. It is still here. It shows kids a future. Older people remember when it was new. There are not many churches. They are often empty. But the basketball courts are full. All the houses look different, but they feel the same. There is a big store called Super A. A big family from Yemen owns it. They are the only Arab family in the neighborhood. Most people are African American.

The streets are wide. Kids play football. They stop for cars. Many people have lived here for a long time. They know each other. There was a karate school, but it is now a drugstore. Kids do not want to be like the Karate Kid anymore. There is a small movie theater. It shows old movies cheaply. Young people do not like it. Older people like it. They enjoy a night out.

There is a big road that goes through the town. The entrance and exit are in the next town. People wanted an entrance and exit here. Young people supported it. Older people said no. They said it would ruin the town. The city agreed. They are building a new school. We are choosing a mascot. I think a cyborg with a country accent and a log cabin would be good.

This is a small area. It has houses and stores. You might not think it has many interesting places. There is a big old store that is not used. There are also some hotels. People only stay there for a few weeks each year.  If you walk behind these places, you will see a lot of small apartment buildings. They look like toys put together. Some apartments are bad. We will not talk about them. But other apartments are good. 

Near the apartments is a school. It is small. Students go there to study. They walk to class in the morning. Some drivers get angry at them.

There is a road that goes to another area. There is a park and a hospital there. The hospital helps people who are hurt. There are kids playing in the park. There are also old people walking their dogs. 

There is a shopping area near the park. There is a place to eat sushi, a swimming store, and a place to get your nails done. You can do many things there. There is also a place to buy frozen yogurt. Teens like to eat there.

This area is like a small town. It is quiet and peaceful.

She asked, "Where is everything?"  We drove past the corn fields. "This is it!" I said. She would be shocked by how empty it looked. She was from a town where the store was close. She had never seen so much open space.  I told her what it was like to grow up in rural Ohio. In that moment, she understood me and where I came from.

We drove on a small road.  You will see a lake.  Near the lake is my house. The houses are mostly made of brick and stucco. Each house has a big yard. People take pride in keeping their yards nice. In spring, there are many flowers and trees. The driveways have fancy cars, like Mercedes. They shine in the sun after a car wash.

As we drive toward my house, my Korean neighbor is always outside. He mows his lawn all day and sings. Everyone laughs, but he is a kind person. He was a doctor, but he is older now. He blends in with the grass and his mower.

My house is here. Geese are in the side yard. Our dog chases them.  There is a little stream behind the house. You can hear frogs, the stream, and cows from the farms.

Across a wooden bridge is a special place. There are trees, plants, and flowers. I played there as a child. I built forts and chased animals. There were always friends to play with.

Winter is very cold, but it is beautiful. The yard is empty. Trees are bare. Sometimes it snows. A winter wonderland appears. There are snow angels and snowmen. My sister and I fought a lot. We used snowballs as weapons. We built forts to keep our snowballs. We played pretend in our winter world. We were just kids, happy and free.

Portland, Oregon has a special feeling. People say it is "weird." The town has a sign that says, "Keep Portland Weird." Some people say this is a memory of Portland from long ago, a place where things were different and people made their own fun. Other people see it as an invitation to come be weird with them. 

Portland has changed a lot. Many people from California have moved here. There are many new buildings. But Portland is still weird. "Weird" means accepting things that are not normal. 

Portland has many things like other cities. There are yoga classes, people who dress in a special way, and people who work in offices. Maybe weird means that people in Portland do not take things too seriously.

In my neighborhood, houses are colorful. People grow plants in their yards. There are boxes on the street where people put things they no longer need. You can find clothes, books, or even strange things in these boxes. 

This is what Portland is like to me. There are many different kinds of people here. Some people do yoga with goats, or go to soccer games. 

Portland has problems like other cities. There is a problem with drugs and homelessness. The weather can be sad, and that may make things harder.  But Portland is a place where people try to follow their dreams.

The mountains are always there. They are in the north. Every day, they see the sun rise and set. I forget about them sometimes. I am busy with work and life. But they are still there. They do not change. They do not care about life’s problems. When I am stressed, the mountains call to me. When I look at them, I feel calm. They give me strength. 

I moved here when I started college. The mountains north of campus were the first thing that caught my eye. The university is beautiful, with its buildings, ponds, and trees. But the mountains are special.

The town is also nice. There are many cafes where students study. The downtown area has old buildings. It feels like a city. But it is not far from the quiet town. This mix of places makes the town interesting.

I have made many happy memories here. I walked past the park swings with friends after studying all night. We watched movies at a fancy theater.

The town also has sad memories. The ponds are good for thinking. I have cried there at two in the morning. I wondered about my life.

I walked past the pond, the park, and the small houses. I walked until I reached a main street. The sun was shining on the palm trees. The sky was blue and yellow. As I looked up, I saw the mountains. They were there, like always. They were bigger than any building. They made me feel strong.

You will not have a hard time finding Bensonhurst, Brooklyn. Public transportation is easy to use and is very popular in New York City. Bensonhurst is a city neighborhood. You will still feel like you are in New York City. During your visit, you will see many Asian stores. Over the last twenty years, Bensonhurst has had many new Asian people move in. You will see an Asian store on almost every block. The most popular stores are supermarkets and laundromats. These stores are very popular with people who live there. The food is good, the prices are low, and it is easy to go there. Near me, there are four Asian supermarkets within two minutes of each other. This makes it easy to buy food.

Bensonhurst is not only for Asian people. It is very diverse. There are immigrants and their children who were born in America. Most of the big businesses are owned by Asian people. There is also a new park nearby. It has ten basketball courts, a big field for soccer or baseball, four handball courts, swings, a playground for kids, and a water fountain. The park is very diverse.

There are not many big businesses in Bensonhurst. You will mostly see buildings for apartments or houses. Most people live in two-family houses.

Most of the people are nice, but they are very loud. You will hear cars playing loud music or people speeding by. 

If you are visiting at night, be careful. Bensonhurst is safe, but people can be unpredictable. You might meet people who want to start trouble. I was bullied here once, but that was a long time ago. Recently, there have been problems with people stealing packages.

Another problem is that people do not clean up after their dogs. Despite a city rule, you will see dog waste everywhere. My biggest complaint is seeing dog waste on the floor. Be careful and keep your shoes clean!

My home is on a big hill. There are not many sidewalks. People call it the "work out hill" because runners like to go up it.  There are no sidewalks on my street, so people walk in the road. The road is bad in some places. Some wires are old and look bad. It rains a lot, so branches fall on the wires.

There are many tall trees. People do not like them. They want to cut them down because the trees block the view of the ocean. Many houses are on the hill to see the water. At sunset, the water shines and the sky is orange. It is often cloudy, so the sun is not very bright. It is often wet and damp. Moss grows on everything.

There are not many children. There is a school nearby, but most people are old. People have dogs. They walk in yards or run in the street. Dogs like to go into houses if doors are open.

Rabbits live here. Some are big. Gardeners do not like them because they dig in gardens. My cats like rabbits. We do not see many rabbits now.

We have small birds and hummingbirds. Sometimes a hawk or eagle flies by, but crows chase it away.

There are no stores nearby.  There are a few restaurants at the water. There is not much beach, but the rocks are fun to throw in the water. The bay is not wide. We can see the other side.

I live in a small town. It is in the southern part of Tennessee. My house is on a street that connects two big roads. There is lots of car traffic. But it is still a quiet place. Most people have lived here for a long time. They keep busy with yard work and daily tasks. In the winter, we go sledding down a hill. We live at the front corner of our street. We see everyone who goes by. We know most cars that drive here. If we see a new car, we pay attention. Some neighbors walk for exercise or to walk their dogs. Kids ride bikes, like in any neighborhood. We work from home. There are four of us: my wife, our two daughters, and me. My daughters are eleven and fourteen years old. Everyone knows us. We go outside to play, even in the rain. Sometimes we have a barbecue on our back deck. It smells good. It seems like someone is always cutting grass. We hear lawn mowers almost every day from spring to fall. We have many trees in our neighborhood. It was once a forest. There is a lot of shade, but lots of leaves in the fall. We have to rake and burn the leaves every year. I like the smell of burning leaves. It means fall is here. We haven't had much winter lately, so it feels like a long fall. Our garage is in the back of our house. We rarely use the front door unless someone knocks. I like to work on my truck and other projects in the garage. When the garage doors are open, I feel more connected to the neighborhood. On holidays, it is quiet. Thanksgiving is busy because families visit. There are extra cars parked everywhere. It is the same for Mother's Day and Christmas. I like living here. It would be perfect if it were not for the traffic.

My neighborhood is in the middle of the high desert. There is dirt everywhere. People who have not lived here may not know how it feels to see only brown. When you see a green lawn, you know the person who owns it pays a lot of money to keep it that way. When I first lived here in the 1990s, houses were far apart. Now there are more houses, but they are still spread out. It looks more like a city every day. But most places are changing. The people here are usually friendly, like in any city, there are good parts and bad parts. I live in a nice neighborhood with lots of friendly older people.

The stores here are mostly big chains, like Food 4 Less and Smart & Final. If you want better stores, you have to travel. I do not see many Whole Foods or stores like that. Most of the jobs in my city are in construction. I think this is because the city is still growing. There is lots of open space to build. This makes me nervous because I like it the way it is. I moved from a big city and I do not want to go back.

My job is in construction. I install drywall and T-bar. I like the animals in my home. People come to the high desert for many reasons, one of which is the beauty of the desert. The desert has special plants and animals that need protection. People who live here should learn about the animals to live together safely. My family and I get along well with the animals. My three children love lizards and bugs. They are outside now trying to catch them.

Victorville has some attractions. It is a good place for families to experience the desert. You can visit the San Bernardino County Fair every year. It is fun for everyone. You can also go to Wrightwood to see the snow-covered mountains and take winter sports lessons.

The Victor Valley Museum has interesting things to see. It has rocks, fossils, Native American things, and old objects that tell the story of Victorville.

My neighborhood is not like other neighborhoods. I live on a college campus. My house is a dorm. My neighbors are the other students who live here. I also see the campus as part of my neighborhood.  Even though it is different, my neighborhood has some things in common with other neighborhoods. It has houses, people, stores, and a park. 

Let's talk about the houses. There are three kinds of houses: apartments, regular houses, and dorm rooms. Apartments have two to four people in each room. There are four to six rooms on each floor. Most buildings have two floors. So, about twenty people live in each building. Regular houses are for rent. They usually have two to four bedrooms and are mostly for alumni. There are not many of these. Dorm rooms are the most common. They have two people in each room.

My school has people from many different places and ages. Professors and staff live in the houses. New students live in dorms. Older students live in apartments.

The stores on campus are like stores in other neighborhoods. There are places to eat and stores that sell things like clothes and food. You can find almost anything you need on campus. There is also a park. It is clean and safe because everyone takes care of it.

I have lived in my neighborhood for about ten years. When I first came here from Riverdale to Stockbridge, I was sad. I missed my old friends and family. My parents wanted a better life for me and my sister, so we moved.  Stockbridge is a nice place with good schools and houses. 

At first, it was hard to make new friends. I made some friends at school, but also some enemies. I got to know my neighbors, Mr. Glen and his children, and Dennis. They are good people, almost like family.

I went to Mr. Glen's wedding with my family. It was fun! I caught his wife's garter, but not the flowers. We danced all night. I enjoyed talking with Marsharii, one of his daughters. I hope she is doing well. 

My neighborhood is like a maze, but now I use GPS to explore. I have gone to the park with my friends Kason and Curtis. We play video games and have fun.

Sometimes I go to the park to enjoy nature. It makes me feel calm and peaceful. I like to practice balance with sticks from Home Depot and bring my bokken wooden sword. 

There is a basketball and tennis court, but I haven't played in a while. My dad taught me and my best friend to play tennis with Mr. Graves. We had fun practicing. 

There are many happy memories from this neighborhood, and I am excited for more to come!

My house is near my school. I like living here. There are many apartment buildings. There are also some small restaurants and bars. These places are not very expensive. One bar changed its name and is now more expensive. But the drinks are good. Most people here are students or have low incomes. The apartments are not very cost. There are many children because there is a school near my house.

I do not know my neighbors. I do not want to. They smoke a lot of marijuana. The building manager put air freshener near their door. This is funny. The buildings are old, but the insides are modern. Down the street are new apartments. But I do not like them. They are built poorly. They cost a lot to rent, but they are near the school.

There is a cheap restaurant near my house. They serve food on paper plates. Most of the food is microwaved. Across from the restaurant is a gas station. People say it is a bad place to work. The city repaired the road last summer. Now there is a good sidewalk, grass, and the area is nice.

My apartment building is surrounded by trees. They cut down some trees, but there are still many. Behind my building is another set of apartments. My street is 42nd Street. Behind it is 43rd Street. It is not as nice. The sidewalks are bad. The buildings look old. There are many trees on this street. They hide the buildings.

Most crime in my area is at an apartment complex on 43rd Street. But other apartment buildings have crime too. I like where I live. It is affordable and close to things I need. I like that the school is close and I can take the bus to the store and downtown.

My home area has small houses. They are close to each other but look like they are far apart. All the houses are yellow with white front steps and green metal roofs. Most people know each other. We talk at the end of our driveways in the evening. The young kids play. It is nice to be away from computers and cars. It feels like a different time. We live near fields and trees. The sky is blue with white clouds. The bad thing is, we have had storms with tornadoes. Last night, we heard the loud sirens. I went to my bathtub with my small dog, my purse, and some pillows. My big dog stayed in the living room and barked. The hail fell very hard. The road got hot because of the change in temperature. The hail melted quickly. Then the sun came out and it rained. A double rainbow appeared! I took pictures to show my friends. The streets were quiet for a while. Then people came home. It was like nothing happened. We talked and ate dinner. My neighborhood is friendly. I like the way people talk here. I moved from New Hampshire to North Carolina. I have a small apartment, like everyone else. The outside looks the same but the inside is different. Some are very small, which is strange. I like to walk in the big field behind my house. There is a pond there. I have seen deer and a big frog. It is a good place to live. It is forty minutes from Charlotte. Every morning, roosters crow from the farms. It feels like a small village. There is a donkey on a farm nearby. We hear him in the evening. I am happy to live here.

I moved to this area when I was about to start eighth grade.  It was hard to make friends at first, but I became close to two people.  One lives two houses away, and the other lives on my street. They do not live there now, but I still remember them. Most of the people who lived here when I first moved are still here. My neighborhood is like most American suburbs.

There are many two-story houses. I hear kids playing outside every weekend, or any time the weather is warm. The area is quiet most days. I have never had a problem with anyone here. People leave you alone unless you need help. I have ordered many things online and never had anything taken from my porch. I trust my neighbors. 

There is a park near my house. I have many memories there. I played basketball, football, and baseball with other kids. I also got hurt there once playing football. I got hit in the nose. But the good memories are better. Now, I go to the park to spend time with my cousin's children. They are much younger. They like to play on swings and slides. Just thinking about the park makes them happy. It makes me feel nostalgic for many reasons.

My neighborhood is very diverse. There are many kinds of food nearby. You could find Chinese, Indian, Mexican, and Italian restaurants all within one mile. Many people use apps like GrubHub and DoorDash to get food delivered.

Fast food places are popular, but you can find those in any suburb. There are many pizza places too.  There are stores that sell everything you need. There are many dry cleaners. There is a Walgreens, a CVS, and a Jewel-Osco grocery store on the same street. There is even an Indian-owned store if you want to buy ingredients for Indian food or ready-made meals.  

Overall, I like my neighborhood. Reading about problems others have with their neighbors makes me grateful for mine.

My town is small. It is in South Carolina. It is not big like other towns. But, it is important for farming. Johnston is known as the Peach Capital of the World.  There are many peach trees and farms with cows.

Most houses are far apart. They are two stories tall. Some have metal roofs to keep cool. The houses are back from the road. This lets people grow food in front.

In the center of town is one stop light.  There are a few stores here. There are three places to get fast food: Hong Kong (a Chinese restaurant), Fiesta (Mexican food), and Gary's (burgers). There used to be a pizza place, but it closed.

There is a small drug store called Maxwell and Halford. They are famous for their Cherry Coca-Cola.  There is also a grocery store called IGA. It is small, but people often go to a bigger store in another town for most of their food. The most popular store is Dollar General. It sells many things and is always busy.

There is a furniture store called Possibilities. It is run by a nice woman. They even have movers! Next to the furniture store is a place to take care of pets. They do grooming, daycare, and more.

The doctor and vet are outside the main part of town. They are small, but good. There is one elementary school. Older students go to school in another town.

There are no parks in town, but they are making one. People want more places to go. There are no movie theaters, bowling alleys, or places for kids to play.

It is a quiet town. You could drive through and not even notice it!

I first heard about my area on a podcast about missing people.  It was a little strange.  All the apartments cost more than one thousand dollars a month. I never heard this story.  My friends did not know it, either.  Maybe it is hard to live here. I know some friends are sad. Things cost a lot, but we learn to save money. You like old toys and clothes from stores that are not new. When you grow up, you smell different. You might smoke or be used to how things are. But, old stores are always there. The smell of being an adult is old magazines. They are on a piano that is not used. The smell goes into the leather and stays even after you wash it.  There are three used clothing stores near here. You can go to two charity stores, a library, a store with old books, and a store with strange things. Downtown is busy. Cars and people fill the streets every day. But you do not hear it in the stores. No matter how many people are around, the store is quiet. It is a good place to spend time.  Every year, there are more cars and people. It is a growing city, they say. It has one of the biggest online store companies. It is still changing. It reminds me of New York City. Everyone has their own goals. No one asks for much from you. You can be alone, quiet, and do your own thing. People will not bother you. It is not like the South, where if you care about someone, people think you are nice. People here do not ask about your life. You can stay quiet as long as you want. The city will continue like waves on the beach. It is a fun place to live. The man next door plays the piano and two people upstairs sing.  There is always something happening.  We are more like friends than just people who live near each other. We help each other. We have parties, we go to funerals, and we help each other when we need it. I am lucky to live here. I like most of my neighbors. They are good to me. I clean up after myself and give them food, and they do the same. I bring them mail, and they bring me mail. It is nice to see them, and I think they like me too. I live in a big, boring building, but my neighbors make me feel like I did not make a big mistake in life.

My neighborhood is like many others. It is a suburb.

There is a group that makes sure everyone follows the rules. The houses look the same. They are small and have yards with grass, rocks, and short driveways. Every house has a garage for two cars. The roads are new and smooth.

Most houses are one story, but some are two. We do not have mailboxes in front of each house. Instead, there are mailboxes at the end of the street. Everyone has a key to open their box. There are also big boxes for packages.

My home is near the edge of the city. It feels like both a suburb and the country. We have many things to do, like pools and walking trails.

Many people here are old. It is a safe place, and people help each other. There are also some middle-aged and young people who work.

The city is big, but it feels small. We have all the things we need, like a mall. It is not very big, but it has many stores. It takes about 15 minutes to drive to the mall. We have stores for food, clothes, and other things.

My neighborhood is safe and nice. We have good things here, and it is easy to go to the city when we need to.

I live in a small town. It is near a big city. My neighborhood is on the east side of town. It is one of the poorer parts of town. Most houses are rented to people with low incomes. But it is not a bad place to live. My neighbors are kind. They say hello when I walk by. Crime is a little higher here than in other parts of town. There have been some bad things happen close to my home, like shootings and even a murder. Our neighbors lost their son in a shooting last year. We have not been hurt by crime, but things sometimes go missing from our porch.

Our town has been hurt by the opioid problem. Many people have died from drug overdoses. But there are things to help people with this problem. There are places to go for help with addiction. There are classes to teach people how to help others with addiction.

My son goes to a good elementary school. The teachers and staff are great. He has special needs, but he is not bullied. The school is a good place for him. There is a group of parents who help the school. They do many things to help the school and families.

Because so many people in town are poor, the school gives free breakfast and lunch to all the students. No child goes hungry. The school does not treat any child badly because they cannot pay. School fees and supplies are not expensive.

The city government has made the town look nicer. They have fixed the roads and parks. But most of these changes are in the center of town, where the stores are. The east side where I live is not as nice.

I like living in this town. The people are friendly. The schools are good. There are stores to buy what we need. Our house is not very valuable, but it is comfortable. We have lived here for a long time, and we like it here.

My neighborhood is full of culture. It is on a hill with old buildings. I live in a seven-story apartment building. It is across from the old live theater. A block away is a small bar. People like to go there on warm nights. Many people wait in a line to get in. There is a park near my home. It is big for this part of town. The park has a wall made of concrete. There are tall steps in the wall. In the winter, homeless people sleep in their tents near the steps. It does not snow much, but it rains a lot. The rain can be hard in the winter. The people sleep close together to stay warm. They are also near a place where they can bathe and shower.

I like my city. It has old buildings and good architecture. But I like the people the most. My neighborhood was once dangerous. People say the government tried to stop the violence. The people remember this history. They work hard to keep their neighborhood clean. They care about their city. Some people say that white people should not walk in the neighborhood at night. I think this is from the past. Maybe people see me as one of them, because I am dark. I know racism is a problem. People make assumptions about others.

I know one thing: my neighborhood is home. I feel safe walking there at night. People have been kind to me. A laundromat owner stayed open late so I could charge my phone. Someone gave me money and told me I was beautiful.

I live in a small town in Michigan. It is in a place where you see farmlands and small towns for tourists. There are no big stores like malls or Wal-Mart. You must drive to go anywhere. My town is near two big lakes: Lake Michigan and Lake Charlevoix. You find beaches everywhere. 

My neighborhood is like a small town. Houses are spread out, not close together. They are old homes, some new, some old. Many have full basements you can see from the street. Many have old aluminum siding. The houses are all colors. Most have yards with things like trampolines and playsets. Some people have gardens or fences for animals. 

The people here are hardworking. They work to make a living and raise families. You see kids playing, people walking dogs, and others biking or rollerblading. Neighbors know each other. You know who is from here and who is not.

The lawns are nice. People take care of them. The grass is green and cut short. Plants and bushes are trimmed. It is not a fancy neighborhood, but it feels safe and good for families. It is quiet and peaceful.

Near my house is the sheriff's office, jail, health department, and recycling center. People from the town use these. There are baseball and softball fields near there, and a small airport. You can hear planes taking off and landing. You can walk to get ice cream, and it is not far to the town center. My kids can bike to the park, which is eight blocks away. This is a great place to live.

original_texts:
I live in Rural America, specifically small town Michigan. Where you go from farmland to small tourist cities. There is no big city malls, no Wal-mart, Target, or even an Applebee’s. Anywhere you need to go, you have to drive to get to. Despite that I live in one of the most beautiful places in the world surrounded by water. My “city” is surrounded by water. Beautiful Lake Michigan to one side, and Lake Charlevoix on the other. Everywhere you go you can find a beach to dip your toes in. My neighborhood, reflects the idea of small town. Houses are not stacked upon one another. They aren’t cookie cutter houses that are built the same. They are older homes, some of them being updated and remodeled some of them being older. Most homes have basements. Full Basements that you can see from the road. Many houses in the neighborhood have older aluminum siding. We have houses every color you can imagine in the blocks that surround my house. Most of the houses have yards. Yards with trampolines, and playsets. Some people have gardens, and fences for their animals. The houses resemble Middle America. Hard working people who work to make a living and are either raising families or have raised families. On any given day you will see kids running up and down the streets. You will also see people walking dogs, biking and rollerblading. Neighbors know neighbors and you can recognize who fits in and who doesn’t belong. You will see someone grilling outside and wave, or even someone that is walking their dog from a few blocks down and smile pleasantly. The lawns are kept in decent condition. Nobody has leaves piled up from fall time. Green grass is kept mowed and under control. If people have plants and bushes in their yards they are kept trimmed down. It isn’t a beautiful neighborhood that you drive into and think wow look at the nice homes, but one you drive into and think you can tell this would be a good place to raise a family. It’s quiet, peaceful and, and safe. While only average looking, it is exceptional for the fact that it represents what people want in the world, which is a safe place to land at the end of the day. Within walking distance there is the county sheriff’s department and jail. The Health department is just next to that. The city recycling center sits just down the road, and neighbors and residents from around the city utilize the services they provide. We have baseball and softball fields nearby where you can hear the announcers keeping score and calling the names of players. Our small town airport is next to that. You can be playing outside, or even inside and hear the rumbles of small engine planes taking off and landing. You can walk to get ice cream from the local ice cream place, and if you are really into it you can make it downtown from our neighborhood of homes. My kids can ride their bikes to the park which is only 8 blocks or so away. It is a really great place to live.
The general area in which I live in can be described as your typical cookie cutter suburbia. For my neighborhood in particular, the presence of a homeowner's association is very apparent. Upon entering, you'll see nothing but well-maintained single family homes, which we can thank the homeowner's association for. The front yards are all very similar. There's a small patch of landscaped grass, some decorative pebbles, and rather short driveways. Every so often you'll see small trees as well. Everyone has a two car garage. As you continue to drive along throughout the neighborhood you'll see newly paved concrete. Despite many different families living here, the roads are in excellent condition. You won't find any potholes or anything like that here. Most of the houses are single story, but sometimes you'll see two stories as well. We don't have a typical mailbox set-up that you would expect for single family homes. There are no individual mailboxes in front of each house. Instead, it's more like apartments where there are a large grouping of mailboxes at the end of the street. Everyone uses a key to gain access their specific mailbox. And there's two larger lockers for packages. Again, you can thank the HOA and their obsession with uniformity for this. The location of my house is on the extreme edge of the nearby city, so my neighborhood can be described as part rural, part suburbs. As a result, we have a lot of land for, well, everything. There's multiple community pools to which anyone living here can access. It's well maintained and gated. And then there are various walking trails where you can walk your dog, or just go for an evening stroll by yourself. You don't have to visit a park to get your exercise in. The neighborhood is large enough that you can simply run around it and get more than enough exercise. Most of the community is made up of retired people. It's a very safe area, and everyone looks out for one another. Mixed in with that, we have a small amount of middle aged and young professionals too. In regards to the city, it's surprisingly large - at least by population - but also has a small time town feel. We have the vast majority of amenities that you come to expect and rely on. For example, we have a exactly one mall. It's not huge, but it gets the job done. For me, it takes around 15 minutes of driving to get anywhere significant, but once I do that, I am greeted with many different stores to choose from. We have everything from high end grocery stores where you can get organic food, to bargain outlets that only stock a small selection of items and has bare minimum staff to keep costs down. All in all, my neighborhood is safe, well-maintained, and pretty typical. We have a lot of nice things, like pools and walking trails. And although we aren't right next door to any sort of shopping, you can just hop in a car and go to any major chain that you'd like.
The first time I'd heard of my place, I was listening to a podcast about people who'd gone missing. It was a little surprising. Almost every apartment in the area was going for over a thousand dollars a month. I'd never heard anything about that story and neither had any of my friends. Maybe it's the struggle. I know a few of my friends cry themselves to sleep at night. Things are expensive, but we've learned how to be frugal over the years. You start to like the dusty smell of flea market toys and mothballed clothes. You smell a lot less in adulthood. You might start to smoke, or you might just be too accustomed to the state of things. But the flea market always asserts itself. The smell of adulthood is dusty magazines stacked on a closed piano. It wedges itself in the leather and stays in even after you wash it. Here, there're 3 thrift stores in walking distance. If you start on the far side, you can patronize two charity thrifts, a library, a rare book store, and a curio shop. Downtown is dense, cars and people fill the streets every morning, but you'd never hear it in the thrifts. No matter how many people or cars pass by, the store is silent. It's a nice place to lose an afternoon. Every year, there's more and more of those. Cars and people flood it. It's a developing city, they say. Headquartering one of the largest online empires for e-commerce and delivery, it's still showing growing pains. It reminds me of New York. Everything and everyone is set on their own goals, and there isn't a whole lot anyone asks from you. You can be alone, quiet, and independent, and people will leave you alone. It's not like the South, where being a little concerned means you care. You don't pry into anyone's life here, really. You can keep up your shell as long as you'd like, and the city will crash and roll back like waves on the beach. It's a lively place to be. Between the pianist next door and the two amateur vocalists upstairs, there's always something going on. In a way, we have less of an apartment of strangers and more a community of friends. We come together for our needs, celebrate birthdays, mourn funerals, and help each other when we can. In a way, I'm lucky to be here. I quite like most of my neighbors and they treat me pretty well. I try to make sure to clean after myself and leave them food and they do the same in kind. I bring mail to them and they to me. It's nice to see them and I believe they enjoy my presence as much as I do theirs. I live in a massive, dehumanizing modernist sprawl but it's people like my neighbors that make me feel like I didn't totally ruin my life.
I live in a small Midwestern town that is just outside the suburban areas of a major city. My immediate neighborhood, on the east side of the town, could be described as the most economically disadvantaged area of the town. Property values are low, with most houses being rented to or owned by low-income individuals. However, it is not unattractive or unpleasant. My neighbors are generally friendly people who will smile and say hello when I walk down the street. Crime rates, while slightly higher than other parts of town, are still generally low. There have been a few violent crimes in the past ten years within a few blocks of my home, including a few shootings and at least one homicide. Our next door neighbors lost their son in a shooting outside an area bar last year. Fortunately, our family has not been directly affected by crime other than having an occasional item disappear from our porch if we forget to bring it inside. In general, the town in which I live has been profoundly affected by the “opioid epidemic” that has affected many parts of the United States. Many lives have been lost due to fentanyl overdoses. Fortunately, there are many resources in my town to combat this epidemic, including several addiction rehabilitation centers and Narcan training sessions for families and friends of those affected by addiction. Despite these challenges, this town has many positive attributes. My son’s elementary school has excellent staff, from the principal to the teachers and support staff. Despite having special needs, he has not faced any bullying thus far due to the incredibly positive atmosphere of the school, and he loves it there. We have an active PTO that plans multiple events throughout the year to promote family involvement and educational progress. Because over 20% of our town’s population lives below the poverty level, the elementary school provides free breakfast and lunch to all students, so that no child ever has to go hungry. No child or family is treated as “less than” due to an inability to pay, and costs for school fees, supplies, and field trips are very reasonable. The City Council and staff have made many improvements to the appearance of our town, including repaving roads, landscaping, and refurbishing city parks. Unfortunately, most of these improvements have taken place in the center of town and on the west side, where all of the shopping areas are located and most of the traffic passes through. The east side where I live tends to be neglected, which is a point of contention for those in my neighborhood. Overall, I do enjoy living in this town. People are generally friendly, the schools are great, there are enough shopping options (both small businesses and larger retail stores) to meet my family’s needs, and our home may not be worth much, but it is comfortable and adequate. Our family has lived here for over 16 years, and we cannot imagine living anywhere else.
My neighborhood is full of culture. It's set upon a hill, surrounded by buildings with historical meaning. I live in a 7 story apartment building right across from the old live Theater, and a block down The Hill, is this cool little arcade bar that different types of people flock to on warm summer nights. Often times, especially on the weekends in June and July, you will see a line of people waiting to get in. A few blocks up is the nearest city park. It's pretty big considering the part of town it sits in. Encircling the park is concrete, with tall stairs poured into the wall. During the frigid winter months, homeless people set their tents up in neat little rows along the sidewalk and along the wide steps. It doesn't snow much, but it rains, and the torrential down pour in the mid-winter months often tends to make it difficult to keep warm. Setting their tents up close together, in the center of town rather than out in the jungle, keeps them much warmer. They're also within reasonable walking and transit distance to the only family center for miles, where they can bathe and shower. What I love about my city though, isn't the beauty of the historic nature- the tall proud buildings, the architecture that is spattered through-out the varying levels of the hills that roll down towards the ocean. What I love about my neighborhood is the culture of the people themselves. You see, Hilltop once was the most notorious neighborhood on the West Coast for gang violence. You still hear stories, even three decades later, about the federal government officials and the DEA sweeping through like a broom, trying to clean the streets. The people, they don't forget. Stories are still passed from generation to generation, on through to transplants like me, of those days. The people work hard, even though it's still considered one of the rougher 'hoods' in the entire city, to keep it cleaned up. They still care about what goes on in their city, on their block. They say that if you're white, you shouldn't walk around the Hill after dark. Truly, I believe that this warning is reminiscent of the old days, and it is tinged with the sour taste of social conditioning. Perhaps it is that I am just dark enough to pass for a not entirely "white-girl," or maybe Hilltop recognizes me as one of their own, someone who is just as painfully aware of the reminders that constantly plague our nation. Reminders that racism, cultural conditioning, and assumptions are made out of ignorance and fear, even in a city that is supposed to be a cultural melting pot Utopia. I know one thing: no matter how far I roam, the Hilltop is home. I feel alive walking those streets at night, meeting people who have more quickly and rarely nefariously offered me a jacket than to rob me. It's a place where laundromat owners have stayed open just a few minutes later so I could charge my phone when I had no where to escape from the rain. It's a place where I have sat, believe myself to be invisible, huddled against concrete store fronts on the most grey dreary of nights, only to have someone stop and look me in the eye, hand me a $5, and tell me I'm beautiful and valuable.
I moved to this neighborhood just when I was about to start eighth grade. It was hard for me to make friends at first, but I ended up getting close to someone who lives two houses down from me and another guy that lives on my street. Neither of them lives there anymore but the memories are still there. The same people who lived here when I first moved here are still here for the most part. My neighborhood is pretty similar to your average American suburban neighborhood. The neighborhood has a lot of two-story houses in it. Every weekend or just whenever it is warm outside I hear the kids playing outside. The neighborhood is quiet most days of the week. I have never had a problem with any of the people in the neighborhood. You are left alone in this neighborhood unless you need help. I have ordered multiple packages online and have never gotten a package snatched off of my porch. I feel like I can trust my neighbors. There is a park a minute or two away from my house. I have a lot of memories there. I have played basketball, football, and baseball there with the other guys in the neighborhood before. I also ended up with one of my worst memories there when I got elbowed in the nose playing football, but the good memories outweigh the bad. Nowadays, whenever I go to that park it is to spend time with my cousin's kids. They are much younger than me and still like playing on swings and slides and all of that type of stuff. Just the thought of going to the park makes them excited. The park makes me very nostalgic for a number of different reasons now. The neighborhood is very diverse. You will find all kinds of food nearby. In just a one mile radius, you would be able to find Chinese, Indian, Mexican, and Italian restaurants. However, nowadays, a lot of people just use apps just as GrubHub and DoorDash to get their food delivered to them. The most popular food places are the fast food shops but you can get those near pretty much any suburban neighborhood. There are also plenty of pizza places. The stores here contain everything you would ever need. There are multiple dry cleaners nearby. There is a Walgreens and a CVS on the same street as well as a Jewel-Osco grocery store, which is popular in the Midwest. Some of the stores are even diverse as there is an Indian-owned store if you are ever in the mood to make some homemade Indian food or to buy some ready-made Indian food. Overall, I am a fan of my neighborhood. Reading on social media and seeing on the news some of the horror stories other people have to go through with their neighbors makes me grateful for mine.
My neighborhood is nearby to the college that I attend, and for that I quite enjoy living there. There are mostly apartment buildings, but a few restaurants and bars that are fun to go to and aren't terribly expensive to go to. One of the bars was just renamed, and that one is more expensive to go to but it isn't really the worst quality of service or drinks there. Most of the people are nice. They are either college kids or they are lower income, since the apartment housing isn't very expensive. There's a lot of children nearby since there is an elementary school within walking distance of my apartment. I don’t know my neighbors, but I don’t really want to. They smoke a lot of weed and so the management of my building put an air freshener unit right across from their door, which my boyfriend and I found very funny. It’s almost insulting. The buildings that are around me are usually pretty old looking but might have renovated interiors. Down the street a bit there are brand new apartments, but I don’t like them because I know the construction done on them wasn’t particularly good. They’re cheaply built but the rent is expensive, which I think is such a scam but because they’re near campus, the management of those buildings can get away with it. There is a really cheap restaurant about five minutes from where I live that serves food only on paper plates and most of what they make is microwaved. Then across from that is a gas station, which I’ve heard isn’t a very good place to work. But thanks to some money from the city, the road was redone last summer so that there’s a nice big sidewalk, lots of grass on the medians and sides of the roads, and now the area is a little nicer. But the apartment building I live in is shrouded in tress. They cut a few of them down, so there are a few stumps, but there are a lot more trees where I live than down the road. Behind my apartment complex is a tree line and then another set of apartments. I live on 42nd street, but right behind is 43rd street and that one isn’t as nice. The sidewalks are really bad and falling apart, and most of the buildings on it look shabby. There are a lot of trees on this street, but that is probably to hide what the buildings look like. Most of the crime in my area has happened at an apartment complex on that street, but then again, I can’t blame just them. There are apartments across the street from me that also have a lot of crime and a rather transient population. But I think I like where I live. I can afford it, and there’s plenty of useful amenities nearby. I especially like how the university is within walking distance and there are two bus stops so that I can get to the store and downtown with ease.
My neighborhood is made up of duplex's on a cul-de-sac. They are intermittently placed and spaced so that they look like individual houses. The only difference is each is painted yellow with white porches and green metal roofs. Almost everyone, but not all, are friends with each other. We stand at the end of a not pre-decided driveway some evenings and chit chat while the small children of the neighborhood play with their toys, sidewalk chalk or fly their kites. It is very refreshing in this modern all to mechanical/computer filled world. It is rather like stepping back in time. We are surrounded by fields and trees enhanced by blue skies and white billowing clouds. The only downfall? This season, we are experiencing tornado warnings and for the first time, last night we actually heard actual tornado sirens so we had to head towards shelter. Sure enough, you would have found me in my bathtub clutching my littlest dog along with my purse and a few pillows. My big dog wanted nothing to do with the bathroom and remained in the livingroom, nervous and barking, nervous about the odd circumstances. The neighborhood was quiet except for the sound of large hail which fell all bout the ground. After the storm the road literally was steaming from the change of temperature. We went from 92 to 75 in a matter of minutes. The hail immediately melted when it hit the hot pavement. As I looked up towards the clearing skies, the sun came out and it started to rain. A double rainbow apparated. I ran into the house and grabbed my camera. Quickly snapped pictures to share with my Facebook friends and family. They were in awe, as was I. The streets remained quiet for another hour, before some people finally came home from wherever they were when the thunderstorm hit. Then it was business as usual, mom’s and children outside as dinner cooked. Such a friendly neighborhood for this gal who has recently moved form NH to NC. I adore the southern accent that people speak with. I have a two bedroom and two bath apartment, as does everyone. Though all the houses look the same on the outside, not all of the apartments are the same on the inside. Some are actually quite tiny. It doesn’t make sense to me. I love to walk along the biggest field behind where I live and mosey down to the pond that is not made for swimming. I have seen deer and in the morning you can hear the giant bullfrog singing his song. It is a fantastic place to live just forty minutes outside the city of Charlotte. Each morning is welcomed by the sound of roosters crowing from the surrounding farms. It is rather like living in a small community village of it’s own. We even have a donkey at a nearby farm that you can hear braying in the evening to let us know he is there. I was lucky to find this gem of a neighborhood.
Well, considering that I’ve been here for about 10 years, I guess I can share what I know. First off, I was pretty sad when I first came to my neighborhood. I came from Riverdale to Stockbridge, and I’m not going to lie, I cried, because I missed them and I loved them.. but my mom and dad wanted the best for me and my little sister, so we moved to a better location for housing, a better high school, everything was considered “not ghetto” when we moved to our new neighborhood. Throughout the years, I got used to it, and made some new friends, and some new enemies too in school. I never really truly got to know my neighbors throughout the years, except Mr. Glen and his children, as well as Dennis for a bit, both being right next to us. They have been enjoyable people that I almost can consider as family in some ways, and I truly do appreciate them. I remember when me, mom, dad, and my sister went to Mr. Glen’s wedding (They got re-married) It was really fun and enjoyable to say the least, and something I’m looking forward to someday, as I build my wealth and give my future wife the life of a Queen. When Mr. Glen’s wife, Ms. Veda, took off the white little strap on her leg and threw it, I caught it! Sadly I didn’t catch the flowers! We all danced the night away, and I really enjoyed having a good time with Marsharii, one of their daughters. I haven’t seen her since though. I hope she’s moved on to bigger and better things. The neighborhood itself is like a maze, although now I have a GPS, so I can take more time to explore it. I’ve only went so far, and that is when I’ve hung out with my friends Kason and Curtis. We all used to play video games alot, and just enjoy life to the fullest as much as we could. Sometimes I would go to the park and enjoy nature, which soothes my soul. It gives me a sense of calmness and peace these days. I’ll also bring some sticks that I bought from home depot and just practice my balance, And bring my bokken wooden sword if I can,. I have fun enjoying what I love to do. There’s also a basketball and tennis court, although I haven’t played tennis or basketball in a long time, It’s still nice to have in case I ever want to pick it back up and give it another go. My dad grew me and my best friend up on Tennis with Mr. Graves, and we’d always have a great time.. They worked us hard! But we always had fun. I guess there’s a lot of times I’ve had fun in this neighborhood, and there’s plenty of stories, but these are what really stuck out to me, and I believe that the best, is yet to come!
My neighborhood is a quaint little town. It doesn't stand out from any other in South Carolina, but it's got a significant impact on the agriculture sector. Johnston is known as the Peach Capital of the World, something that the town proudly boasts about on the welcoming sign. It's primarily composed of farmland dominated by either peach trees or cattle. Houses that aren't located within the main part of town are widely spaced apart; most are two stories with either metal roofs to help combat the blazing summer heat or gray shingles. More often than not these houses aren't located near the road, but are further back allowing for the front fields to be used for animals/crops. Within the main part of town, there's a single stop light that hangs at a four way. Here is where the only stores in the entire town are located. There are three places in which you can get "fast food': Hong Kong, a small Chinese restaurant run by a single family, Fiesta Mexican Restaurant, or Gary's, a small burger chain. There used to be a pizzeria, however it closed down a short time ago. There is a very small family-owned pharmacy called Maxwell and Halford Drug; funnily enough, they're best known for the Cherry Coca-Cola they sell. There is a small, but expensive grocery store called Independent Grocers Alliance, more commonly known as IGA. While it is the only grocery store in the entire town, many individuals only stop to pick up one or two items; most prefer to travel to a Walmart in Batesburg-Leesville in order to purchase the majority of their groceries. The most popular store in the entire town is Dollar General; this store sells a vast array of everyday items and it often busy from the moment it opens until closing time! There is a very small furniture store, Possibilities Furniture & More, run by a kind woman who is well-known within the community. The store has been in Johnston for a plethora of years and even employs two movers who will deliver the purchased furniture! Attached to the furniture store building is a small pet groomers called Clark's Cuts and Kennels. They provide a multitude of services such as daycare, boarding, grooming, nail grinding, bathing, etc. Both a doctor's and veterinary practice are situated away from the primary part of town; they are both very small practices, though well-equipped to aid the residents of Johnston. There is a single elementary school called Johnston Elementary School. Once students have completed fifth grade, they must attend both middle and high school in the next town over. There are technically no parks within the town, however they are currently in the midst of creating a 2.5 acre recreational area in order to provide families with more opportunities to enjoy outings and attract more visitors/potential residents. Admittedly there isn't much to do; there are no movie theaters, bowling alleys, "hang out" spots, playgrounds for children, areas to walk pets, or a large variety of restaurants. Despite this it's a nice town, so small that you could pass in the blink of an eye without realizing!
I live in a typical suburb area in a small southern town in Tennessee. It's a connecting street between two state highways, so we get a bit more traffic on the street than I'd like, but other than that, it's a quiet neighborhood. There's not too many folks that move in and out, so I've grown used to most of the people that live in the neighborhood. People busy themselves with yard work and other daily chores for the most part. In the winter, we sled down a hill on our side street. We live in a house at the front corner of our street, so we see everyone coming and going all day long and are familiar with the cars that people drive around here. Whenever we see a strange vehicle, we tend to take note of it. Some of the neighbors go walking for exercise or just to walk their dogs. Kids play on their bikes and all that you would expect from that. We are at home a lot since we work from our house. There are four of us, Myself and my Wife, and two Daughters ages eleven and fourteen. So, I'd say that everyone else is used to us coming and going as well. We get outside and play, sometimes even in the rain. Once in a while we grill outside on our back deck and it's always a pleasant smell from the barbecue and all. It seems that there's always someone cutting grass around here and you can hear a lawn mower nearly every day from March through about October, when the grass finally stops growing. We have a lot of trees in our neighborhood as it was originally a wooded area, so there's lots of shade, but there's always a lot of leaves in the Fall as well. So, that means raking and burning the leaves on a yearly basis. I like the smell of burning leaves too, so that's always a nice sign that Fall has arrived. Lately, we've not been having much Winter to speak of, so it just feels like a long Fall. Our garage is at the back of our house, so we seldom use the front door of our house unless someone knocks on the door, which is rare. I like to work in the garage on my truck or other projects from time to time and when I have the garage doors open, it feels like I'm more tuned into the neighborhood. On holidays it is pretty quiet around here. Thanksgiving sees some of the neighborhood families visiting with people from out of town and there are extra cars parked everywhere during that time of year. It's the same at other holidays like Mother's day and Christmas. All in all, I like living here. If it weren't a through street, it would be perfect.
